1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:03,600
User defined functions are well defined by you.

2

00:00:03,600  -->  00:00:08,280
This means that we can write almost anything that we can imagine to accomplish our goals.

3

00:00:08,280  -->  00:00:11,380
Let's say that we want to print a greeting to a user and say,

4

00:00:11,380  -->  00:00:14,765
Hello World, every time a certain function runs.

5

00:00:14,765  -->  00:00:18,500
Python does not come pre installed with a function to do this,

6

00:00:18,500  -->  00:00:24,490
but it does come with pre installed abilities for us to write a function to do this.

7

00:00:24,490  -->  00:00:26,740
We will do this by writing a function called

8

00:00:26,740  -->  00:00:30,000
greet that will then print the message Hello World.

9

00:00:30,000  -->  00:00:32,280
This combines the use of the built in

10

00:00:32,280  -->  00:00:36,520
function print inside of our user defined function called greet.

11

00:00:36,520  -->  00:00:38,680
Let's test this out by writing it.

12

00:00:38,680  -->  00:00:42,655
We'll write def greet,

13

00:00:42,655  -->  00:00:48,520
and then we'll say print Hello World.

14

00:00:48,520  -->  00:00:53,320
We'll end quote there and then we'll end the print C. When we run this function,

15

00:00:53,320  -->  00:00:57,880
we should see our message that looks like this.

16

00:00:57,880  -->  00:01:01,610
We'll define this function and we'll call it.

17

00:01:01,610  -->  00:01:05,300
Just like that, we see our message Hello World.

18

00:01:05,300  -->  00:01:08,270
But this is impersonal and generic.

19

00:01:08,270  -->  00:01:12,170
If we wanted to make this more customized and dynamic to the user,

20

00:01:12,170  -->  00:01:14,430
how can we update our user defined

21

00:01:14,430  -->  00:01:18,270
greet function to greet an actual user with their name?

22

00:01:18,270  -->  00:01:19,950
If you remember from earlier,

23

00:01:19,950  -->  00:01:22,930
functions allow us to pass in an optional input,

24

00:01:22,930  -->  00:01:28,350
which could be one or more values that we can use to customize how our functions run.

25

00:01:28,350  -->  00:01:33,410
We can pass in a name value into our function in order to make a customized greeting.

26

00:01:33,410  -->  00:01:35,830
Let's see how to do that here.

27

00:01:35,830  -->  00:01:41,660
We'll take our base of our greet function.

28

00:01:41,970  -->  00:01:44,350
We'll pop open a new cell,

29

00:01:44,350  -->  00:01:47,605
and we'll say def greet input.

30

00:01:47,605  -->  00:01:52,850
Then we'll pass in name as an input,

31

00:01:52,850  -->  00:01:56,630
we'll say return, and then we'll return in F string,

32

00:01:56,630  -->  00:01:59,170
and we'll say hello,

33

00:01:59,170  -->  00:02:01,710
and then in curly brackets,

34

00:02:01,710  -->  00:02:07,710
name exclamation point, and then closed quotation marks.

35

00:02:07,950  -->  00:02:13,795
Then we'll call our function, greet input.

36

00:02:13,795  -->  00:02:18,280
Then we'll pass in Python coder.

37

00:02:18,280  -->  00:02:21,950
Now, because we are using an F string to

38

00:02:21,950  -->  00:02:27,310
define a string with a dynamic input of the name value,

39

00:02:27,310  -->  00:02:30,720
can you guess what the output of this will be?

40

00:02:30,720  -->  00:02:33,490
Let's run this and find out.

41

00:02:33,950  -->  00:02:37,530
You should see hello Python coder,

42

00:02:37,530  -->  00:02:41,930
and that's because we pass this in as an input into our input function,

43

00:02:41,930  -->  00:02:47,070
which passes that into this output. Pretty cool, right?
